By contrast, Benoit Assou-Ekotto was banned for three matches and fined £50,000 for congratulating Anelka via Twitter on making the gesture, which is viewed as being anti-Semitic.

Since joining Liverpool from AC Milan for £16million, Balotelli has rarely been out of the headlines, thanks to his poor form, swapping shirts with Real Madrid defender Pepe at half-time during a Champions League game and questions about his attitude.

He will miss Saturday's game against Sunderland at Anfield as he recovers from a groin problem that he suffered on international duty.

This is a crucial period for the club and Brendan Rodgers is adamant there will be no distractions.

He said: ‘Sunderland is a big game. Basle, Manchester United away, the League Cup game the week after. It’s a period of big games. I need to choose a team that’s going to be fit and fresh.’

